%description:
TCP Workstream H1: MSG_EOR record boundary. Based on tcp_nagle_3.test's exact
scenario (same sendScript, same Nagle-coalescing setup) with "eor" added to
the first write. Without eor, tcp_nagle_3.test's own trace shows segment
A005 (2049:3073) spanning past byte 3001 -- the end of the first (3000B)
write -- into the second write's data, since TcpSendQueue is a pure
byte-range buffer with no per-SEND boundary concept. With eor marked on the
first write, sendSegment() must never build a segment crossing sequence
number 3001: this test pins the resulting re-segmentation, most visibly the
disappearance of any segment spanning that boundary.

Falsification: tcp_nagle_3.test itself, run unmodified (same sendScript
minus the eor keyword), is the falsification baseline -- it already pins the
boundary-crossing segment A005 (2049:3073) that this test's fix eliminates.

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false

*.testing=true

*.tcptester.cmdenv-log-level=DEBUG
*.*_app.cmdenv-log-level=DEBUG
**.cmdenv-log-level=OFF

# script format: "time numbytes[ eor]; time numbytes[ eor]; ..."
# Same as tcp_nagle_3.test, with "eor" added to the first (3000B) write.
*.cli_app.sendScript="1.00 3000 eor; 1.0005 2000; 2.00 3000; 2.0005 100"

include ../../lib/defaults.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Unaffected by eor: the very first segment ships immediately (nothing outstanding
%# yet), same as tcp_nagle_3.test's unmarked baseline.
%contains: stdout
[1.001 A003] A.1000 > B.2000: A 1:1025(1024) ack 501 win 16384
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The fix: without eor (tcp_nagle_3.test's own baseline trace), the next Nagle-
%# released burst sends a full 1024B segment 2049:3073(1024), spanning past byte
%# 3001 -- the end of the eor-marked first (3000B) write -- into the second
%# write's data. With eor, sendSegment() clamps this segment to end exactly at
%# the boundary (952B instead of 1024B) and sets PSH, since the boundary was
%# reached exactly.
%contains: stdout
[1.205 A005] A.1000 > B.2000: A P 2049:3001(952) ack 501 win 16384
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The following segment resumes cleanly right at the boundary, with the second
%# write's (unmarked) data -- no byte lost or duplicated by the clamp.
%contains: stdout
[1.409 A006] A.1000 > B.2000: A 3001:4025(1024) ack 501 win 16384
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Falsification: the boundary-spanning segment tcp_nagle_3.test pins for this
%# same scenario without eor must NOT appear here.
%not-contains: stdout
2049:3073(1024)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Same total bytes/segments as tcp_nagle_3.test's unmarked baseline -- the clamp
%# only moves a boundary, it neither drops nor duplicates data.
%contains: stdout
Calling finish() at end of Run #0...
TcpTestNet1.cli_app: received 0 bytes in 0 packets
TcpTestNet1.srv_app: received 8100 bytes in 9 packets
[2.409] tcpdump finished, A:11 B:8 segments
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
